    <p class="text-gray-300">We assume that ThresholdCombine is robust, in the sense that if it is run with a set of more than <em>f</em> +1 signature shares, it rejects any invalid ones. In particular, if 2 <em>f</em> +1 shares are provided, certainly a valid subset of <em>f</em> + 1 is among them. In practice, any incorrect shares detected this way can be used as evidence to incriminate a node.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Concretely, we use an efficient threshold scheme <a href="#page-10-15">[11]</a> based on bilinear groups and the Gap Diffie Hellman assumption. We use TSIG to refer to this scheme. The common coin requires only one asynchronous round to complete, and the communication cost is <em>O</em>(<em>N</em>&lambda;) per node.</p>

